ADS 503 Team 4: Predicting Article Shares

Load Data

df <- read.csv("Datasets/OnlineNewsPopularity.csv")
dim(df)
[1] 39644    61

The dataset has 39,644 samples and 61 variables.

Missing Data

na.by.col <- apply(df, 2, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
any(na.by.col > 0)
[1] FALSE

None of the variables are missing any data.

Define Target and Predictors

df <- df[, names(df) != "url"] # drop the url column, which functions as a sample ID
y <- df$shares  # shares is the target variable 
X <- df[, names(df) != "shares"]

Target Distribution

summary(y)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
      1     946    1400    3395    2800  843300 
hist(y)

boxplot(y)

The target distribution is highly right-skewed. Let’s try log transforming it.

hist(log(y))

boxplot(log(y))

The log of the target is much less skewed. Let’s apply the log transformation.

y <- log(y)

Binary Predictors

unique(apply(X, 2, typeof)) # check predictor data types 
[1] "double"
is.binary <- function(x) { # function to check whether or not a variable is binary 
  n.unique <- length(unique(x))
  min <- min(x)
  max <- max(x)
  if (n.unique == 2 & min == 0 & max == 1) {
    return(TRUE)
  }
  else {
    return(FALSE)
  }
}

binary.cols <- names(X)[apply(X, 2, is.binary)]
X.binary <- X[, binary.cols]
X.non.binary <- X[, !names(X) %in% binary.cols]
binary.cols

All predictors are of data type double. 14 of them are binary variables.

Predictor Correlations

There are 12 non-binary predictors contributing to high pairwise correlations. Let’s remove them to avoid multicolinearity issues.

X.non.binary <- X.non.binary[, -high.cor]
cor.matrix.filtered <- cor(X.non.binary)

  cor.matrix.filtered,

Binary Predictors

cor.matrix <- cor(X.binary)
corrplot(
  cor.matrix, 
  method = "square", 
  type = "upper", 
  order = "hclust"
)

high.cor <- findCorrelation(cor.matrix, cutoff = .7) # variables contributing to high pairwise correlations 
names(X.binary)[high.cor]
[1] "is_weekend"

One of the binary predictors contributes to pairwise correlations greater than .70. Furthermore, there is a binary indicator for every day of the week, so we need to remove one to avoid the dummy variable trap.

X.binary <- X.binary[, -high.cor]
X.binary <- X.binary[, names(X.binary) != "weekday_is_sunday"]

Let’s also check the channel variables for the dummy trap.

channels <- c(
  "data_channel_is_world",
  "data_channel_is_socmed",
  "data_channel_is_tech",
  "data_channel_is_bus",
  "data_channel_is_entertainment",
  "data_channel_is_lifestyle"
)
summary(apply(X[, channels], 1, sum)) # check if they always sum to 1 for every sample
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
 0.0000  1.0000  1.0000  0.8453  1.0000  1.0000

They do not always sum to 1 for every sample, so they do not fall into the dummy variable trap. Let’s update our master predictor matrix to only retain the non-redundant predictors.

cols.to.keep <- c(names(X.non.binary), names(X.binary))
X <- X[, names(X) %in% cols.to.keep]

Split the Data

set.seed(100)
trainingRows <- createDataPartition(y, p = .80,  list = FALSE)
y.train <- y[trainingRows]
y.test <- y[-trainingRows]
X.train <- X[trainingRows, ]
X.test <- X[-trainingRows, ]
idx <- createFolds(y.train, returnTrain = TRUE)
ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", index = idx)
